and","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Schotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1115–1180":"about 1115–1180","1115–1180":"1115–1180","1122–Male":"1122–Deceased","1123–Male":"1123–Deceased","1118–1160":"1118–1160","1150–1189":"1150–1189","1085–1140":"1085–1140","1094–1124":"1094–1124","about 1150":"about 1150","adult 1153":"1153","1140":"1140","1085":"1085","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1094":"1094","1180":"1180","1118":"1118","1115":"1115","1124":"1124","about 1149":"about 1149","1189":"1189","1123":"1123","1122":"1122","about 1115":"about 1115","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cunynghame","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish:  see  Cunningham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cunningham","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the province of Cunningham in Ayrshire, first recorded in 1153 in the form <i>Cunegan</i>, a Celtic name of uncertain origin. The spellings in <i>-ham</i>, first recorded in 1180, and in <i>-ynghame</i>, first recorded in 1227, represent a gradual assimilation to the English placename element <i>-ingham</i>.","Irish: surname adopted from Gaelic <b>Ó Cuinneagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cuinneagán</i>’, a personal name from a double diminutive of the Old Irish personal name <i>Conn</i> meaning ‘leader, chief’. This name is also adopted for <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Connagán</i>’, from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Conn</i>.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Wernebald de Cunynghame, who was granted the manor of Cunningham by Hugh de Morville in the early 12th century."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Cunynghame was born about 1115, in Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Wernebald De Cunninghame, was 31 and his mother, Alice Wernebald, was 23. He married Riscinda De Barclay about 1149, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1180, in Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, at the age of 66."},"et":{"about 1115–1180":"umbes 1115–1180","1115–1180":"1115–1180","1122–Male":"1122–Surnud","1123–Male":"1123–Surnud","1118–1160":"1118–1160","1150–1189":"1150–1189","1085–1140":"1085–1140","1094–1124":"1094–1124","about 1150":"umbes 1150","adult 1153":"1153","1140":"1140","1085":"1085","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1094":"1094","1180":"1180","1118":"1118","1115":"1115","1124":"1124","about 1149":"umbes 1149","1189":"1189","1123":"1123","1122":"1122","about 1115":"umbes 1115","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Kil